I'm trying to have a nested router `use`d by a bigger one while also sanitizing a param (an ID) globally, so that it doesn't have to be done in each nested page.
It seems that `req.params` gets overridden at every nesting, so any sanitization prior to that gets discarded.

Repro:
```js
import express, {Router} from 'express';
import {param, query} from "express-validator";

// Sanitization middlewares
const sanitizers = [
    param("id").isInt().toInt(),
    query("test").isInt().toInt()
]
// Handler for both example pages that outputs the types of the param and the query
const requestHandler = (req, res) => {
    res.send({
        paramType: typeof req.params.id,
        queryType: typeof req.query.test
    })
}

const app = express()

// By putting the sanitizers in the router use() middlewares the param sanitization gets discarded
const doesntWork = Router({mergeParams: true})
doesntWork.get("/", requestHandler)
app.use("/doesnt-work/:id", sanitizers , doesntWork)

// Putting the sanitizers directly in the pages middlewares works OK
const works = Router({mergeParams: true})
works.get("/", sanitizers, requestHandler)
app.use("/works/:id", works)
```

In this small example I've declared two routes `/works/:id` and `/doesnt-work/:id`. Both also accept an int query parameter `test` that isn't affected.

Results:
* `/works/1?test=2` outputs `{"paramType": "number", "queryType": "number"}`
* `/doesnt-work/1?test=2` outputs `{"paramType": "string", "queryType": "number"}`

I didn't find any documentation for this behavior, nor any bug report. I'm guessing that the culprit is the `mergeParams` options, but it obviously cannot be omitted, otherwise the `id` param won't be visible at all in the nested router.


Thanks in advance for the help!

