comments.body:
So in order to make sure a route is authenticated before being accessed, we need to add an `authenticate` middleware to it.
eg.
```
router.post('/data', authenticate, (req, res, next) => { console.log('inserting data'); });
```
`console.log('inserting data');` will be executed only if the `authenticate` middleware calls `next()`.

There are 2 ways of writing this `authenticate` middleware:
1.
```
const express = require('express');

const router = express.Router();

router.use((req, res, next) => {
  // returns true if cookie contains valid session id and user is deserialised
  if (req.isAuthenticated()) { 
    next();
    return;
  }
  res.sendStatus(401);
});

module.exports = router;
```
2.
```
const authenticate = (req, res, next) => {
  if (req.isAuthenticated()) {
    next();
    return;
  }
  res.sendStatus(401);
};

module.exports = authenticate;
```

Both can then be imported with `const authenticate = require('...')` and used in the above `router.post` example.

Which way of writing this middleware (1 or 2) is preferred?

