Hi, I quess it's intended bahavior, however I would like to know why is that.
The next() in a context of a single router immidiately invokes next middleware registered on that router.
So if there is a code placed after next(), it's invoked after the next middleware is finished:

``` javascript
router.use(function(req, res, next) {
    console.log("1");
    next(); // immidiately invokes next middleware
    console.log("3");
}).use(function(req, res, next) {
    console.log("2");
    next();
});
// outputs: 1 2 3
```

However when middleware is wrapped into another router this behavior will change.
The next() will instruct the router to call next() on it's parent's stack, but only after the current middleware is completely finished:

``` javascript
router.use(express.Router().use(function(req, res, next) {
    console.log("1");
    next(); // the parent's next middleware is called after this one is finished
    console.log("3");
})).use(function(req, res, next) {
    console.log("2");
    next();
});
// outputs: 1 3 2
```

Maybe it's because the request object is changed inside the router, so if the next() would immediately invoke parent's middleware, the request object would change again, so it wouldn't correspond with the request intially passed to router?
