The following code should respond with "forbidden" but instead executes the route handler and responds with "was not cancelled".

If the route is created before the middleware is installed, then the method handlers installed after the middleware cannot be cancelled by the middleware, the middleware does not even run in this case.

```
var express = require('express');

var router = express.Router();
// NB: if the route is created here, before the middleware is installed, then it cannot be cancelled by the middleware
var route = router.route('/test');

router.use(function(req,res,next) {
    // cancel execution
    console.log('cancelling execution');
    res.send("FORBIDDEN\n");
});

route.get(function(req, res) {
    console.log('execution was not cancelled');
    res.send("WAS NOT CANCELLED\n");
});

express().use(router).listen(8123);
```

comments.body:
The output is correct for this code, handlers are executed in the order they were registered.

This is due to the fact that `router.route()` is a shortcut to the attached `{methodname}` handlers.

@sjanuary Is also correct, that the middleware will be called if you tell your route to also call to the next middleware, although usually that isn't what you'd do. (Typically routes are endpoints after regular middleware.)

@sjanuary whatever you feel is necessary, but afaik this is the correct behavior.

