to handle an URL like: `/thumb/canada/news-events/event-list/185-Roma_Ghezzi[1].jpg/75x75`

Adding the character `\\]` will make the route stop working, even if the URL doesn't contain those characters.

Even worst when you try adding the characters `\\(` or `\\)` because it crashes the process with the error:

```
SyntaxError: Invalid regular expression: /^\/thumb\/(?:([a-zA-Z-0-9\/ \._%,&[]))]+)\/(?:([^\/]+?))\/?$/: Unmatched ')'
    at new RegExp (<anonymous>)
```

I'd really prefer to use this a rule like the following one:

``` javascript
router.get("/thumb/:file(.+)/:size", function (req, res) {
