comments.body:
Correct, it is a limitation, and our dependency has an update that may fix it, but it's not backwards-compatible, so it can never land inside express 4.

Another thing is that the URL above, `/thumb/canada/news-events/event-list/185-Roma_Ghezzi[1].jpg/75x75` should be coming into your server as `/thumb/canada/news-events/event-list/185-Roma_Ghezzi%5B1%5D.jpg/75x75`, which you would be able to match using a regular express in your URL.

For one thing, you can never match on `/` within the part regular expressions, as they only are supposed to span a single path component. You may be interested in the `*` character in the path, which may satisfy your needs:

``` js
router.get("/thumb/:file*/:size", function (req, res) {
   //do stuff
});
```

As a last resort, the path itself can be whatever regular expression you like:

``` js
router.get(/^\/thumb\/(.+?)\/([^\/]+)\/?$/, function (req, res) {
   //do stuff
});
```

Ok I understand, URLencoding the file name is a good point. However, this regex:

``` javascript
router.get("/thumb/:file*/:size", function (req, res) {
   //do stuff
});
```

doesn't work as expected as it returns these params:

URL: /thumb/canada/news-events/event-list/1.jpg/75x75

``` javascript
{ '0': '75x75',
  file: 'canada',
  size: '/news-events/event-list/1.jpg' }
```

Instead, this rule 

``` javascript
router.get(/^\/thumb\/(.+?)\/([^\/]+)\/?$/, function (req, res) {
//do stuff
});
```

works perfectly as it produces:

``` javascript
{ '0': 'canada/news-events/event-list/1.jpg', '1': '75x75' }
```

Thanks!

